===Determiner===
{{en-det}}

# Each of the two; one and the [[other]]; {{non-gloss definition|referring to two individuals or items}}
#: {{ux|en|"Did you want this one or that one?" — "Give me '''both'''."}}
#: {{ux|en|'''Both''' children are such dolls.}}
#* {{w|Bible}}, {{w|Book of Genesis|Genesis}} xxi. 27
#*: Abraham took sheep and oxen, and gave them unto Abimelech; and '''both''' of them made a covenant.
#* {{w|Henry St John, 1st Viscount Bolingbroke|Viscount Bolingbroke}} (1678-1751)
#*: He will not bear the loss of his rank, because he can bear the loss of his estate; but he will bear '''both''', because he is prepared for both.
# Each of the two kinds; one and the other kind; {{non-gloss definition|referring to several individuals or items which are divided into two groups}}
#: {{ux|en|I ate five strawberry sweets and three chocolate sweets. '''Both''' were very tasty.}}
#* {{quote-magazine|date=2013-07-19|author=[http://www.theguardian.com/profile/iansample Ian Sample]
|volume=189|issue=6|page=34|magazine={{w|The Guardian Weekly}}
|title=[http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2013/jul/08/irregular-bedtimes-affect-childrens-brains Irregular bedtimes may affect children's brains]
|passage=Irregular bedtimes may disrupt healthy brain development in young children, according to a study of intelligence and sleeping habits.&nbsp; &para;&nbsp;Going to bed at a different time each night affected girls more than boys, but '''both''' fared worse on mental tasks than children who had a set bedtime, researchers found.}}

